And then exits. The flow is:On the first call to , it returns 0 and saves its caller's context in .Then we set  to 666 and  to  with the value 1. returns 1, so we  and exit.Note that we have to mark  as  for the program to reliably print 666. Otherwise, the compiler is allowed to optimize the access to  and have it return 42 instead. This might happen in the following ways:The compiler could constant fold  to 42. This will happen in the example if we remove  and use any optimization level above . Then  gets printed.Say that constant folding doesn't happen, maybe because we insert a  right after the definition of . In that case, the compiler could register-allocate  in a callee-save register, in which case the register ends up saved by . This also leads to  being printed.Say that we experience register pressure for some reason, and  doesn't make it into a callee-save register, but instead gets spilled. At any optimization level above , the compiler will split  into two variables: one for  and one for , and the printf will reference the first one (since dominates the ). Those two variables will  get separate spill slots. Hence, when we come out of the  the second time, reading  will still give 42.Three things to reflect upon:To get the property that 's value is observed to be 666 in the printf, we need to make sure that the compiler treats  as a stack allocation rather than a variable. Using  achieves this. Also, passing a pointer to  to anywhere is likely to accomplish this.Spill slots are not the same as stack allocations. If a variable is stack-allocated, then it will get one stack allocation. If a variable is spilled, it may get multiple spills (often, a separate spill per assignment).The compiler is allowed to analyze the lifetime of spill slots and stack allocations. It's allowed to reuse spill slots. How does the compiler know that the  spill slot should stay alive until the  happens? How come it won't get reused, resulting in  having either 666 or any random garbage when we fall out of the  a second time?Here's a more diabolical version of the example that triggers spilling of  to two different spill slots (one for 42 and one for 666) in gcc, clang, and filcc.#include <setjmp.h>
#include <stdio.h>

int main(int argc, char** argv)
{
    int x = 42;
    asm volatile("" : "+r"(x));
    jmp_buf jb;
