Now, the results I see are:The unsafe thing that is happening (and that Fil-C prevents by refusing to compile this program) is that if the compiler compiles a call to without knowing that it's calling  then the spill slot used by  might get reused by some other variable in the code after the .Fil-C makes / memory safe by ensuring that:The  just contains a pointer to an opaque  object. The contents of this object cannot be accessed from Fil-C. Only the Fil-C runtime can manipulate it. This works because most code never inspects the innards of  (and code that does will not work in Fil-C). Note that if you do overwrite , then you'll most likely cause a Fil-C panic when you try to , because the internal implementation of  will check that it can load a  from the . There is no way to spoof a  from Fil-C.It's only possible to mention the  symbol by calling it directly; anything else will ICE the compiler. (And in the future, it might even cause the compiler to emit a proper diagnostic.) This ensures that the compiler's machinery for recognizing  (and inhibiting spill slot reuse) always works.The  call is compiled to allocate a new  opaque object and to register the  with the stack frame. Each stack frame can tell you the weak set of  that are valid jump targets for that frame. (It's weak because if the 's are otherwise unreachable, they are removed from that set.) panics unless it is called from a stack frame that is a descendant of a stack frame that considers the  to be valid. This is accomplished by walking the stack and asking each stack frame: do you have my  in your set? Note that repeated s on the same  create new s, and the  is immutable. Hence, membership in the weak set really means that the  call is from a descendant frame.The Fil-C implementations of  and  save and restore a lot of internal runtime state, including the state needed to track GC roots. In particular,  holds a copy of the GC roots of the frame at the time that  was called. So long as the  is live,